1. Introduction

The dataset I plan to use for my self-directed project contains information on Canadian Agency Advertising Gross Spending spanning from 2018 to 2023. Aggregated by Guideline and available via the Government of Canada Open Portal, this dataset offers a comprehensive view, encapsulating over 94% of the national agency spent within Canadas media ecosystem. It provides various insights into agency advertising expenditure, delineating spending by product category, ad revenue allocation, and digital platforms. The dataset specifically includes variables such as Calendar Year, Quarter, Month, Province, Market, Media Type, Media Subtype, and Advertising Spend.

Question:

Has the digitization of technology influenced the landscape of advertising in Canada, challenging traditional methods like radio and newspapers? Moreover, is digital advertising pervasive nationwide, occurring consistently, or is it specifically targeted to certain regions or times?

2. Methods

The data for this analysis was acquired from the Government of Canada Open Portal, which makes comprehensive datasets pertaining to various aspects of Canadian governance and industry publicly available.

Link to Data: https://open.canada.ca/data/en/dataset/c4fef546-d355-4a12-b995-dd8257f55430

After loading in the data, it underwent a cleaning and wrangling process which involved checking for missing values, renaming variables, and creating new variables that will be used later in the analysis. Specifically, I modified the Cal Quarter variable to be numeric in nature as opposed to Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4 as well as added a Season variable (Winter, Spring, Summer, and Fall) since the Quarter variable corresponds to three month periods according to the fiscal calendar instead of seasons. Furthermore, both Media_Type and Region were factored since this will help facilitate categorical variable analysis.

Data exploration and analysis was conducted primarily using various statistical analysis and visualization packages in R including but not limited to dplyr, ggplot2, and tidyr. Both univarite and bivariate analysis was done by creating summary statistics for numerical variables, making frequency plots of categorical variables, faceting bar plots by other variables, and performing regressions.

4. Summary

Based on the preliminary analysis conducted regarding the influence of digitization on the advertising landscape in Canada, several noteworthy trends have emerged. Firstly, there is a clear positive relationship between the amount of money allocated to digital advertising and time, indicating a growing investment in digital marketing. Conversely, traditional methods such as radio and newspapers show declining trends in Canadian advertising spending, suggesting a shifting preference towards digital platforms. Furthermore, the analysis reveals that digital advertising is widely utilized nationwide, in contrast to the more regionally concentrated usage patterns observed with radio and newspapers. While there is a notable concentration of radio and newspaper advertising in Ontario, its important to recognize that the abundance of data entries from this region may skew perceptions of regional advertising trends. Despite these limitations, the results emphasize how digitization has significantly changed Canadas advertising landscape, with digital platforms becoming the primary channels for reaching audiences while traditional methods struggle to remain relevant and effective. However, it is imperative to note that further analysis must be conducted in the next part of this project to examine the nuances of these relationships.
